# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The flexible box layout module (usually referred to as flexbox) is a one-dimensional layout model for distributing space between items and includes numerous alignment capabilities.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This article gives an outline of the main features of flexbox, which we will explore in more detail in the rest of these guides.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When we describe flexbox as being one-dimensional we are describing the fact that flexbox deals with layout in one dimension at a time — either as a row or as a column.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This can be contrasted with the two-dimensional model of CSS Grid Layout, which controls columns and rows together.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When working with flexbox you need to think in terms of two axes — the *main axis* and the *cross axis*.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The main axis is defined by the `flex-direction` property, and the cross axis runs perpendicular to it.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Everything we do with flexbox refers back to these axes, so it is worth understanding how they work from the outset.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Should you choose `row` or `row-reverse`, your main axis will run along the row in the **inline direction**.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Choose `column` or `column-reverse` and your main axis will run in the **block direction**, from the top of the page to the bottom.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The cross axis runs perpendicular to the main axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Therefore, if your `flex-direction` (main axis) is set to `row` or `row-reverse` the cross axis runs down the columns.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If your main axis is `column` or `column-reverse` then the cross axis runs along the rows.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Another vital area of understanding is how flexbox makes no assumption about the writing mode of the document.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Flexbox doesn't just assume that all lines of text start at the top left of a document and run towards the right-hand side, with new lines appearing one under the other.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Rather, it supports all writing modes, like other logical properties and values.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can read more about the relationship between flexbox and writing modes in a later article; however, the following description should help explain why we do not talk about left and right and top and bottom when we describe the direction that our flex items flow in.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If the `flex-direction` is `row` and I am working in English, then the start edge of the main axis will be on the left, the end edge on the right.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If I were to work in Arabic, then the start edge of my main axis would be on the right and the end edge on the left.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In both cases the start edge of the cross-axis is at the top of the flex container and the end edge at the bottom, as both languages have a horizontal writing mode.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] After a while, thinking about start and end rather than left and right becomes natural, and will be useful to you when dealing with other layout methods such as CSS Grid Layout which follow the same patterns.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] An area of a document that is laid out using flexbox is called a **flex container**.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To create a flex container, set the area's `display` property to `flex`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When we do this, the direct children of that container become **flex items**.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can explicitly control whether the container itself is displayed inline or in block formatting context using `inline flex` or `inline-flex` for inline flex containers or `block flex` or `flex` for block level flex containers.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The result of this is that your items will all line up in a row, using the size of the content as their size in the main axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If there are more items than can fit in the container, they will not wrap but will instead overflow.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If some items are taller than others, all items will stretch along the full length of the cross-axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can see in the live sample below how this looks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Adding the `flex-direction` property to the flex container allows us to change the direction in which our flex items display.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Setting `flex-direction: row-reverse` will keep the items displaying along the row, however the start and end lines are switched.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we change `flex-direction` to `column` the main axis switches and our items now display in a column.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Set `column-reverse` and the start and end lines are again switched.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below has `flex-direction` set to `row-reverse`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try the other values — `row`, `column` and `column-reverse` — to see what happens to the content.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] While flexbox is a one dimensional model, it is possible to make flex items wrap across multiple lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you do this, you should consider each line as a new flex container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Any space distribution will happen across each line, without reference to the previous or subsequent lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To cause wrapping behavior add the property `flex-wrap` with a value of `wrap`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Now, if your items are too large to all display in one line, they will wrap onto another line.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below contains items that have been given a `width`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The total width of the items is too wide for the flex container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] As `flex-wrap` is set to `wrap`, the items wrap across multiple lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you set it to `nowrap`, which is the initial value, they will shrink to fit the container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] They shrink because they are using initial flexbox values, including `flex-shrink: 1`, that allows items to shrink.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `nowrap` would cause an overflow if the items were not able to shrink, or could not shrink small enough to fit.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Find out more about wrapping flex items in the guide Mastering wrapping of flex items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can combine the two properties `flex-direction` and `flex-wrap` into the `flex-flow` shorthand.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the live sample below, try changing the first value to one of the allowable values for `flex-direction` - `row`, `row-reverse`, `column` or `column-reverse`, and also change the second to `wrap` and `nowrap`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] We will take a brief look at these properties below, but if you want more comprehensive information, take a look at the Controlling ratios of flex items on the main axis guide.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Before we can make sense of these properties we need to consider the concept of **available space**.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] What we are doing when we change the value of these flex properties is to change the way that available space is distributed amongst our items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This concept of available space is also important when we come to look at aligning items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we have three 100 pixel-wide items in a container which is 500 pixels wide, then the space we need to lay out our items is 300 pixels.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This leaves 200 pixels of available space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we don't change the initial values then flexbox will put that space after the last item.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we instead would like the items to grow and fill the space, then we need to have a method of distributing the leftover space between the items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex` properties that we apply to the items themselves, enable dictating how that available space should be distributed among the sibling flex items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex-basis` is what defines the size of that item in terms of the space it leaves as available space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of this property is `auto` — in this case the browser looks to see if the item has a size.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the example above, all of the items have a width of 100 pixels.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If the items don't have a size then the content's size is used as the flex-basis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This is why when we just declare `display: flex` on the parent to create flex items, the items all move into a row and take only as much space as they need to display their contents.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With the `flex-grow` property set to a positive integer, if there is available space, the flex item can grow along the main axis from its `flex-basis`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Whether the item stretches to take up all the available space on that axis, or just a portion of the available space depends on if the other items are allowed to grow too and the value of their `flex-grow` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Each item with a positive value consumes a portion of any available space based on their `flex-grow` value.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we gave all of our items in the example above a `flex-grow` value of 1 then the available space in the flex container would be equally shared between our items and they would stretch to fill the container on the main axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Where the `flex-grow` property deals with adding space in the main axis, the `flex-shrink` property controls how it is taken away.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we do not have enough space in the container to lay out our items, and `flex-shrink` is set to a positive integer, then the item can become smaller than the `flex-basis`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] As with `flex-grow`, different values can be assigned in order to cause one item to shrink faster than others — an item with a higher value set for `flex-shrink` will shrink faster than its siblings that have lower values.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] An item can shrink down to its `min-content` size.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This minimum size is taken into account while working out the actual amount of shrinkage that will happen, which means that `flex-shrink` has the potential to appear less consistent than `flex-grow` in behavior.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] We'll therefore take a more detailed look at how this algorithm works in the article Controlling ratios of items along the main axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You will very rarely see the `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, and `flex-basis` properties used individually; instead they are combined into the `flex` shorthand.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex` shorthand allows you to set the three values in this order — `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, `flex-basis`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below allows you to test out the different values of the flex shorthand; remember that the first value is `flex-grow`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Giving this a positive value means the item can grow.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The second is `flex-shrink` — with a positive value the items can shrink, but only if their total values overflow the main axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The final value is `flex-basis`; this is the value the items are using as their base value to grow and shrink from.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] There are also some predefined shorthand values which cover most of the use cases.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You will often see these used in tutorials, and in many cases these are all you will need to use.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `initial` value is a CSS-wide keyword that represents the initial value for a property.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Setting `flex: initial` resets the item to the initial values of the three longhand properties, which is the same as `flex: 0 1 auto`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-grow` is `0`, so items will not grow larger than their `flex-basis` size.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-shrink` is `1`, so items can shrink if they need to rather than overflowing.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-basis` is `auto`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Items will either use any size set on the item in the main dimension, or they will get their size from the content size.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `flex: auto` is the same as using `flex: 1 1 auto`; this is similar to `flex: initial`, except that the items can grow and fill the container as well as shrink if needed.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `flex: none` will create fully inflexible flex items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The items cannot grow or shrink and will be laid out using flexbox with a `flex-basis` of `auto`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The shorthand you often see in tutorials is `flex: 1` or `flex: 2` and so on.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This is the same as writing `flex: 1 1 0` or `flex: 2 1 0` and so on, respectively.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The items get minimum size due to `flex-basis: 0` and then proportionally grow to fill the available space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In this case, the `flex-shrink` value of `1` is redundant because the items start with minimum size — they're not given any size that could cause them to overflow the flex container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try these shorthand values in the live sample below.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] A key feature of flexbox is the ability to align and justify items on the main- and cross-axes, and to distribute space between flex items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Note that these properties are set on the flex container, not on the items themselves.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-items` property aligns all the flex items on the cross axis.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value for this property is `stretch` and is why flex items stretch to the height of the flex container by default (or the width if `flex-direction` is set to `column` or `column-reverse`).
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This height may come from the tallest item in the container or the size set on the flex container itself.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You could instead set `align-items` to `flex-start`, or simply `start`, in order to make the items line up at the start of the flex container, `flex-end`, or just `end`, to align them to the end, or `center` to align them in the center.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try this in the live sample — I have given the flex container a height in order that you can see how the items can be moved around inside the container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-items` is set on the flex container and impacts all the flex items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you want to align a flex item differently from others, you can set the `align-self` on the flex item.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `justify-content` property is used to align the items on the main axis, the direction in which `flex-direction` has set the flow.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value is `flex-start` which will line the items up at the start edge of the container, but you could also set the value to `flex-end` to line them up at the end, or `center` to line them up in the center.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can also use the value `space-between` to take all the spare space after the items have been laid out, and share it out evenly between the items so there will be an equal amount of space between each item.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To cause an equal amount of space on the right and left (or top and bottom for columns) of each item use the value `space-around`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With `space-around`, items have a half-size space on either end.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Or, to cause items to have equal space around them use the value `space-evenly`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With `space-evenly`, items have a full-size space on either end.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The article Aligning items in a flex container explores these properties in more depth, in order to have a better understanding of how they work.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] These basic examples, however, are useful in the majority of use cases.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `justify-items` property is ignored in flexbox layouts.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `place-items` property is a shorthand property for `align-items` and `justify-items`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If set on a flex container, it will set the alignment but not the justification, as `justify-items` is ignored in flexbox.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] There is another shorthand property, `place-content`, that defines the `align-content` and `justify-content` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-content` property only affects flex containers that wrap, and is discussed in Aligning items in a flex container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] After reading this article you should have an understanding of the basic features of flexbox.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the next article, we will look at how this specification relates to other parts of CSS.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] CSS grid layout introduces a two-dimensional grid system to CSS.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grids can be used to lay out major page areas or small user interface elements.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This guide introduces the CSS grid layout and the terminology that is part of the CSS grid layout specification.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The features shown in this overview will then be explained in greater detail in the other guides in this series.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A grid is a set of intersecting horizontal and vertical lines defining rows and columns.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Elements can be placed onto the grid within these column and row lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can create a grid with fixed track sizes – using pixels for example.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This sets the grid to the specified pixel which fits to the layout you desire.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can also create a grid using flexible sizes with percentages or with the `fr` unit designed for this purpose.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can place items into a precise location on the grid using line numbers, names or by targeting an area of the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid also contains an algorithm to control the placement of items not given an explicit position on the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can define an explicit grid with grid layout.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The features defined by the grid layout module provide the flexibility to add additional rows and columns when needed.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Features such as adding "as many columns that will fit into a container" are included.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] CSS grid layout and CSS box alignment features enable us to control how the items align once placed into a grid area, and how the entire grid is aligned.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] More than one item can be placed into a grid cell or area and they can partially overlap each other.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This layering may then be controlled with the `z-index` property.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid is a powerful layout method that, when combined with other parts of CSS such as flexbox, can help you create layouts that are responsive, flexible, and accessible.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It all starts by creating a grid in your **grid container**.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We create a *grid container* by declaring `display: grid` or `display: inline-grid` on an element.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As soon as we do this, all *direct children* of that element become *grid items*.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we have a containing div with a class of `wrapper`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We make the `.wrapper` a grid container using `display: grid;`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] All the direct children are now grid items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a web browser, you won't see any difference to how these items are displayed before turning them into a grid, as grid has created a single column grid for the items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If you inspect the grid in your browsers developer tools, you may see a small icon next to the value `grid`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Click this and, in most browsers, the grid on this element will be overlaid in the browser window.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As you learn and then work with the CSS grid layout, your browser tools will give you a better idea of what is happening with your grids visually.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we want to start making this more grid-like we need to add column tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We define rows and columns on our grid with the `grid-template-rows` and `grid-template-columns` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A *grid track* is the space between any two adjacent lines on the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The image below shows a highlighted track – this is the first-row track in our grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid tracks are defined in the explicit grid by using the `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows` properties or the shorthand `grid` or `grid-template` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Tracks are also created in the implicit grid by positioning a grid item outside of the tracks created in the explicit grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We can add column tracks to our earlier example by adding the `grid-template-columns` property, then defining the size of the column tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We have now created a grid with three 200-pixel-wide column tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The child items will be laid out on this grid one in each grid cell.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Tracks can be defined using any length unit.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid also introduces an additional length unit to help us create flexible grid tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `fr` unit represents a fraction of the available space in the grid container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The next grid definition would create three equal width tracks that grow and shrink according to the available space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we create a definition with a `2fr` track then two `1fr` tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Two parts are given to the first track and one part each to the next two tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this final example, we mix absolute sized tracks with `fr` units.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The first track is `500px`, so the fixed width is taken away from the available space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The remaining space is divided into three and assigned in proportion to the two flexible tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Large grids with many tracks can use the `repeat()` notation, to repeat all or a section of the list of grid tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Repeat notation can be used for a part of the list of tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we create an 8-column grid; the initial track is `20px`, then a repeating section of 6 `1fr` tracks, and a final `20px` track.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Repeat notation (`repeat()`) uses the track listing to create a repeating pattern of tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, the grid will have 10 tracks; a `1fr` track is followed by a `2fr` track, with this pattern being repeated five times.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] When creating our example grid, we specifically defined our column tracks with the `grid-template-columns` property, with the grid creating rows as needed to fit the content.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The columns define the explicit grid while the rows are part of the implicit grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The *explicit grid* consists of rows and columns defined with `grid-template-columns` or `grid-template-rows`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The *implicit grid* extends the defined explicit grid when content is placed outside of that grid, such as into the rows by drawing additional grid lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If you place something outside of the defined grid or, due to the amount of content, more grid tracks are needed, then the grid creates rows and columns in the *implicit grid*.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] These implicit tracks are auto-sized by default, meaning the size of the created rows or columns is influenced by both their content and by the available free space within the grid container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `auto` keyword allows the generated tracks to accommodate content while also sharing any remaining space.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can also define a set size for tracks created in the implicit grid with the `grid-auto-rows` and `grid-auto-columns` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we set `grid-auto-rows: 200px`, ensuring the tracks created in this implicit grid are `200px` tall.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] When setting up an explicit grid or defining the sizing for automatically created rows or columns we may want to give tracks a minimum size, but also ensure they expand to fit any content that is added.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] For example, we may want our rows to never collapse smaller than 100 pixels, but if our content stretches to 300 pixels in height, then we would like the row to stretch to that height.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This is solved by the `minmax()` function.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, we use `minmax()` within the `grid-auto-rows` property value.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] By setting `grid-auto-rows: minmax(100px, auto);`, automatically created rows will be a minimum of `100px` tall, and have a maximum of `auto`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Setting `auto` as the maximum value allows the track to grow to accommodate its content (up to its `max-content` size) while also sharing any available free space within the grid container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It should be noted that when we define a grid we define the grid tracks, not the lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid then gives us numbered lines to use when positioning items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In our three column, two row grid we have four column lines.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Lines are numbered according to the writing mode of the document.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a left-to-right language, line 1 is on the left-hand side of the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In a right-to-left language, it is on the right-hand side of the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Lines can also be named, which is discussed in the grid layout using named grid lines guide.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The following example demonstrates basic line-based placement; when placing an item, we target the line rather than the track.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We explore this in greater detail in the grid layout using line-based placement guide.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this example, the first two items on our three column track grid are placed using the `grid-column-start`, `grid-column-end`, `grid-row-start` and `grid-row-end` properties.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Working from left to right, the first item is placed against column line 1, and spans to column line 4, which in our case is the far-right line on the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It begins at row line 1 and ends at row line 3, therefore spanning two row tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The second item starts on grid column line 1, and spans one track.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] This is the default, so we do not need to specify the end line.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] It also spans two row tracks from row line 3 to row line 5.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The other items will place themselves into empty spaces on the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Use the grid inspector in your developer tools to see how the items are positioned against the lines of the grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The longhand values used above can be compressed onto one line for columns with the `grid-column` shorthand, and one line for rows with the `grid-row` shorthand.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The following example would give the same positioning as in the previous code, but with far less CSS.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The value before the forward slash character (`/`) is the start line, the value after the end line.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] You can omit the end value if the area only spans one track.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A *grid cell* is the smallest unit on a grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As we saw in our earlier examples, once a grid is defined as a parent the child items will lay themselves out in one cell each of the defined grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In the below image, the first cell of the grid is highlighted.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Items can span one or more cells both by row or by column, and this creates a *grid area*.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid areas must be rectangular – it isn't possible to create an L-shaped area for example.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The highlighted grid area spans two row and two column tracks.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Any space used by gaps will be accounted for before space is assigned to the flexible length `fr` tracks, and gaps act for sizing purposes like a regular grid track, however you cannot place anything into a gap.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In terms of line-based positioning, the gap acts like a thick, transparent line.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] A grid item can become a grid container.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In the following example, we extend the three-column grid with two positioned items seen earlier, adding sub-items to the first grid item.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As these nested items are not direct children of the grid they do not participate in grid layout and so display in a normal document flow.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we set `box1` to `display: grid`, we can give it a track definition and it too will become a grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The items then lay out on this new grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this case the nested grid has no relationship to the parent.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] As you can see in the example it has not inherited the `gap` of the parent and the lines in the nested grid do not align to the lines in the parent grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In addition to regular grids, we can create *subgrid*.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The `subgrid` value lets us create nested grids that use the track definition of the parent grid.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] To use them, we edit the above nested grid example to change the track definition of `grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr)`, to `grid-template-columns: subgrid`.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The nested grid then uses the parent grid tracks to lay out items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Grid items can occupy the same cell, and in this case we can use the `z-index` property to control the order in which overlapping items stack.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we return to our example with items positioned by line number, we can change this to make two items overlap.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] The item `box2` is now overlapping `box1`, it displays on top as it comes later in the source order.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] We can control the order in which items stack up by using the `z-index` property - just like positioned items.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] If we give `box2` a lower `z-index` than `box1` it will display below `box1` in the stack.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] In this overview, we took a very quick look at the possibilities of grid layouts.
[src:web-platform/basic-concepts-of-grid-layout] Explore and play with the code examples, and then move on to the guide, relationship of grid layout with other layout methods, where we will really start to dig into the details of CSS grid layout.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] The **CSS selectors** module defines the patterns to select elements to which a set of CSS rules are then applied along with their specificity.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] The CSS selectors module provides us with more than 60 selectors and five combinators.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Other modules provide additional pseudo-class selectors and pseudo-elements.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] In CSS, selectors are patterns used to match, or select, the elements you want to style.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Selectors are also used in JavaScript to enable selecting the DOM nodes to return as a `NodeList`.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Selectors, whether used in CSS or JavaScript, enable targeting HTML elements based on their type, attributes, current states, and even position in the DOM.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Combinators allow you to be more precise when selecting elements by enabling selecting elements based on their relationship to other elements.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] The CSS selectors module also introduces the column combinator (`||`).
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Currently, no browsers support this feature.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] The CSS selectors module also introduces the `:blank`, `:current`, and `:local-link` pseudo-classes.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Currently, no browsers support these features.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Overview of the different types of simple selectors and various combinators defined in the CSS selectors and the CSS pseudo modules.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Explanation of the structure of CSS selectors and the terminologies introduced in the CSS selectors module, ranging from "simple selector" to "forgiving relative selector list".
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Lists the pseudo-classes, selectors that allow the selection of elements based on state information that is not contained in the document tree, defined in the various CSS modules and HTML.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Learn how to use the `:target` pseudo-class to style the target element a URL's fragment identifier.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Explores the style limitations set on the `:visited` class for user privacy.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Introduction to basic CSS selectors, including tutorials on Type, class, and ID selectors, Attribute selectors, Pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements, and Combinators.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] Learn the different UI pseudo-classes available for styling forms in different states.
[src:web-platform/css-selectors] The selectors API enables using selectors in JavaScript to retrieve element nodes from the DOM.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-platform/element-form] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The **`<form>`** HTML element represents a document section containing interactive controls for submitting information.
[src:web-platform/element-form] It is possible to use the `:valid` and `:invalid` CSS pseudo-classes to style a `<form>` element based on whether the `elements` inside the form are valid.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Comma-separated content types the server accepts.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The character encoding accepted by the server.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The specification allows a single case-insensitive value of `"UTF-8"`, reflecting the ubiquity of this encoding (historically multiple character encodings could be specified as a comma-separated or space-separated list).
[src:web-platform/element-form] Controls whether inputted text is automatically capitalized and, if so, in what manner.
[src:web-platform/element-form] See the `autocapitalize` global attribute page for more information.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Indicates whether input elements can by default have their values automatically completed by the browser.
[src:web-platform/element-form] `autocomplete` attributes on form elements override it on `<form>`.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The value must not be the empty string, and must be unique among the `form` elements in the forms collection that it is in, if any.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The name becomes a property of the `Window`, `Document`, and `document.forms` objects, containing a reference to the form element.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Controls the annotations and what kinds of links the form creates.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Annotations include `external`, `nofollow`, `opener`, `noopener`, and `noreferrer`.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Link types include `help`, `prev`, `next`, `search`, and `license`.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The `rel` value is a space-separated list of these enumerated values.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The following attributes control behavior during form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The URL that processes the form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This value can be overridden by a `formaction` attribute on a `<button>`, `<input type="submit">`, or `<input type="image">` element.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This attribute is ignored when `method="dialog"` is set.
[src:web-platform/element-form] If the value of the `method` attribute is `post`, `enctype` is the MIME type of the form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This value can be overridden by `formenctype` attributes on `<button>`, `<input type="submit">`, or `<input type="image">` elements.
[src:web-platform/element-form] The HTTP method to submit the form with.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This value is overridden by `formmethod` attributes on `<button>`, `<input type="submit">`, or `<input type="image">` elements.
[src:web-platform/element-form] This Boolean attribute indicates that the form shouldn't be validated when submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-form] If this attribute is not set (and therefore the form ***is*** validated), it can be overridden by a `formnovalidate` attribute on a `<button>`, `<input type="submit">`, or `<input type="image">` element belonging to the form.
[src:web-platform/element-form] Indicates where to display the response after submitting the form.
[src:web-platform/element-form] It is a name/keyword for a *browsing context* (for example, tab, window, or iframe).
[src:web-platform/element-form] This value can be overridden by a `formtarget` attribute on a `<button>`, `<input type="submit">`, or `<input type="image">` element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The **`<input>`** HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `<input>` element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] How an `<input>` works varies considerably depending on the value of its `type` attribute, hence the different types are covered in their own separate reference pages.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If this attribute is not specified, the default type adopted is `text`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `<input>` element is so powerful because of its attributes; the `type` attribute, described with examples above, being the most important.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Since every `<input>` element, regardless of type, is based on the `HTMLInputElement` interface, they technically share the exact same set of attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] However, in reality, most attributes have an effect on only a specific subset of input types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] In addition, the way some attributes impact an input depends on the input type, impacting different input types in different ways.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This section provides a table listing all the attributes with a brief description.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This table is followed by a list describing each attribute in greater detail, along with which input types they are associated with.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Those that are common to most or all input types are defined in greater detail below.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Attributes that are unique to particular input types—or attributes which are common to all input types but have special behaviors when used on a given input type—are instead documented on those types' pages.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A few additional non-standard attributes are listed following the descriptions of the standard attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `file` input type only, the `accept` attribute defines which file types are selectable in a `file` upload control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `color` input type only, the `alpha` attribute provides the end user with the ability to set the opacity of the color being selected.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `image` button only, the `alt` attribute provides alternative text for the image, displaying the value of the attribute if the image `src` is missing or otherwise fails to load.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] (**Not** a Boolean attribute!) The `autocomplete` attribute takes as its value a space-separated string that describes what, if any, type of autocomplete functionality the input should provide.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A typical implementation of autocomplete recalls previous values entered in the same input field, but more complex forms of autocomplete can exist.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For instance, a browser could integrate with a device's contacts list to autocomplete `email` addresses in an email input field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See `autocomplete` for permitted values.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `autocomplete` attribute is valid on `hidden`, `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, `range`, `color`, and `password`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This attribute has no effect on input types that do not return numeric or text data, being valid for all input types except `checkbox`, `radio`, `file`, or any of the button types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See the `autocomplete` attribute for additional information, including information on password security and how `autocomplete` is slightly different for `hidden` than for other input types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A Boolean attribute which, if present, indicates that the input should automatically have focus when the page has finished loading (or when the `<dialog>` containing the element has been displayed).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] No more than one element in the document may have the `autofocus` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If put on more than one element, the first one with the attribute receives focus.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `autofocus` attribute cannot be used on inputs of type `hidden`, since hidden inputs cannot be focused.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Use careful consideration for accessibility when applying the `autofocus` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Automatically focusing on a control can cause the page to scroll on load.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The focus can also cause dynamic keyboards to display on some touch devices.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] While a screen reader will announce the label of the form control receiving focus, the screen reader will not announce anything before the label, and the sighted user on a small device will equally miss the context created by the preceding content.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Introduced in the HTML Media Capture specification and valid for the `file` input type only, the `capture` attribute defines which media—microphone, video, or camera—should be used to capture a new file for upload with `file` upload control in supporting scenarios.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for both `radio` and `checkbox` types, `checked` is a Boolean attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If present on a `radio` type, it indicates that the radio button is the currently selected one in the group of same-named radio buttons.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If present on a `checkbox` type, it indicates that the checkbox is checked by default (when the page loads).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] It does *not* indicate whether this checkbox is currently checked: if the checkbox's state is changed, this content attribute does not reflect the change.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For example, if a checkbox whose `name` is `fruit` has a `value` of `cherry`, and the checkbox is checked, the form data submitted will include `fruit=cherry`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the checkbox isn't active, it isn't listed in the form data at all.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The default `value` for checkboxes and radio buttons is `on`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `color` input type only, the `colorspace` attribute specifies the color space that is used by the `type="color"` input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `hidden`, `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, and `email` input types, the `dirname` attribute enables the submission of the directionality of the element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When included, the form control will submit with two name/value pairs: the first being the `name` and `value`, and the second being the value of the `dirname` attribute as the name, with a value of `ltr` or `rtl` as set by the browser.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When the form above is submitted, the input cause both the `name` / `value` pair of `fruit=cherry` and the `dirname` / direction pair of `fruit-dir=ltr` to be sent.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For more information, see the `dirname` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A Boolean attribute which, if present, indicates that the user should not be able to interact with the input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Disabled inputs are typically rendered with a dimmer color or using some other form of indication that the field is not available for use.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Specifically, disabled inputs do not receive the `click` event, and disabled inputs are not submitted with the form.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A string specifying the `<form>` element with which the input is associated (that is, its **form owner**).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This string's value, if present, must match the `id` of a `<form>` element in the same document.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If this attribute isn't specified, the `<input>` element is associated with the nearest containing form, if any.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `form` attribute lets you place an input anywhere in the document but have it included with a form elsewhere in the document.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `image` and `submit` input types only.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See the submit input type for more information.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `image` input button only, the `height` is the height of the image file to display to represent the graphical submit button.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Global attribute valid for all elements, including all the input types, it defines a unique identifier (ID) which must be unique in the whole document.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Its purpose is to identify the element when linking.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The value is used as the value of the `<label>`'s `for` attribute to link the label with the form control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Global value valid for all elements, it provides a hint to browsers as to the type of virtual keyboard configuration to use when editing this element or its contents.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Values include `none`, `text`, `tel`, `url`, `email`, `numeric`, `decimal`, and `search`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The value given to the `list` attribute should be the `id` of a `<datalist>` element located in the same document.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `<datalist>` provides a list of predefined values to suggest to the user for this input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Any values in the list that are not compatible with the `type` are not included in the suggested options.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The values provided are suggestions, not requirements: users can select from this predefined list or provide a different value.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Per the specifications, the `list` attribute is not supported by the `hidden`, `password`, `checkbox`, `radio`, `file`, or any of the button types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Depending on the browser, the user may see a custom color palette suggested, tic marks along a range, or even an input that opens like a `<select>` but allows for non-listed values.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Check out the browser compatibility table for the other input types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, and `range`, it defines the greatest value in the range of permitted values.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `value` entered into the element exceeds this, the element fails constraint validation.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the value of the `max` attribute isn't a number, then the element has no maximum value.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] There is a special case: if the data type is periodic (such as for dates or times), the value of `max` may be lower than the value of `min`, which indicates that the range may wrap around; for example, this allows you to specify a time range from 10 PM to 4 AM.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, and `password`, it defines the maximum string length (measured in UTF-16 code units) that the user can enter into the field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This must be an integer value of 0 or higher.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If no `maxlength` is specified, or an invalid value is specified, the field has no maximum length.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This value must also be greater than or equal to the value of `minlength`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The input will fail constraint validation if the length of the text entered into the field is greater than `maxlength` UTF-16 code units long.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] By default, browsers prevent users from entering more characters than allowed by the `maxlength` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Constraint validation is only applied when the value is changed by the user.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See Client-side validation for more information.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, and `range`, it defines the most negative value in the range of permitted values.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `value` entered into the element is less than this, the element fails constraint validation.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the value of the `min` attribute isn't a number, then the element has no minimum value.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This value must be less than or equal to the value of the `max` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `min` attribute is present but is not specified or is invalid, no `min` value is applied.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `min` attribute is valid and a non-empty value is less than the minimum allowed by the `min` attribute, constraint validation will prevent form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, and `password`, it defines the minimum string length (measured in UTF-16 code units) that the user can enter into the entry field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This must be a non-negative integer value smaller than or equal to the value specified by `maxlength`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If no `minlength` is specified, or an invalid value is specified, the input has no minimum length.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The input will fail constraint validation if the length of the text entered into the field is fewer than `minlength` UTF-16 code units long, preventing form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The Boolean `multiple` attribute, if set, means the user can enter comma separated email addresses in the email widget or can choose more than one file with the `file` input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A string specifying a name for the input control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This name is submitted along with the control's value when the form data is submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Consider the `name` a required attribute (even though it's not).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If an input has no `name` specified, or `name` is empty, the input's value is not submitted with the form!
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] `isindex`: For historical reasons, the name `isindex` is not allowed.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `name` attribute creates a unique behavior for radio buttons.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Only one radio button in a same-named group of radio buttons can be checked at a time.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Selecting any radio button in that group automatically deselects any currently-selected radio button in the same group.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When tabbing into a series of same-named group of radio buttons, if one is checked, that one will receive focus.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If they aren't grouped together in source order, if one of the group is checked, tabbing into the group starts when the first one in the group is encountered, skipping all those that aren't checked.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] In other words, if one is checked, tabbing skips the unchecked radio buttons in the group.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If none are checked, the radio button group receives focus when the first button in the same name group is reached.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Once one of the radio buttons in a group has focus, using the arrow keys will navigate through all the radio buttons of the same name, even if the radio buttons are not grouped together in the source order.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When an input element is given a `name`, that name becomes a property of the owning form element's `HTMLFormElement.elements` property.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When this code has run, `guestName` will be the `HTMLInputElement` for the `guest` field, and `hatSize` the object for the `hat-size` field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, and `password`, the `pattern` attribute is used to compile a regular expression that the input's `value` must match in order for the value to pass constraint validation.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] It must be a valid JavaScript regular expression, as used by the `RegExp` type, and as documented in our guide on regular expressions.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] No forward slashes should be specified around the pattern text.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] 2. the `'v'` flag is specified so that the pattern is treated as a sequence of Unicode code points, instead of as ASCII.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `pattern` attribute is present but is not specified or is invalid, no regular expression is applied and this attribute is ignored completely.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the pattern attribute is valid and a non-empty value does not match the pattern, constraint validation will prevent form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the `multiple` is present, the compiled regular expression is matched against each comma separated value.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, `password`, and `number`, the `placeholder` attribute provides a brief hint to the user as to what kind of information is expected in the field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] It should be a word or short phrase that provides a hint as to the expected type of data, rather than an explanation or prompt.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The text *must not* include carriage returns or line feeds.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] So for example if a field is expected to capture a user's first name, and its label is "First Name", a suitable placeholder might be "e.g., Mustafa".
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Turns an `<input type="button">` element into a popover control button; takes the ID of the popover element to control as its value.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See the Popover API landing page for more details.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Specifies the action to be performed on a popover element being controlled by a control `<input type="button">`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If you try to hide an already hidden popover, no action will be taken.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If you try to show an already showing popover, no action will be taken.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The button will toggle a popover between showing and hidden.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If the popover is hidden, it will be shown; if the popover is showing, it will be hidden.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If `popovertargetaction` is omitted, `"toggle"` is the default action that will be performed by the control button.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A Boolean attribute which, if present, indicates that the user should not be able to edit the value of the input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `readonly` attribute is supported by the `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, and `password` input types.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See the HTML attribute: `readonly` for more information.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] `required` is a Boolean attribute which, if present, indicates that the user must specify a value for the input before the owning form can be submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `required` attribute is supported by `text`, `search`, `url`, `tel`, `email`, `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, `password`, `checkbox`, `radio`, and `file` inputs.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See Client-side validation and the HTML attribute: `required` for more information.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `email`, `password`, `tel`, `url`, and `text`, the `size` attribute specifies how much of the input is shown.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Basically creates same result as setting CSS `width` property with a few specialties.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The actual unit of the value depends on the input type.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For `password` and `text`, it is a number of characters (or `em` units) with a default value of `20`, and for others, it is pixels (or `px` units).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] CSS `width` takes precedence over the `size` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `image` input button only, the `src` is string specifying the URL of the image file to display to represent the graphical submit button.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `date`, `month`, `week`, `time`, `datetime-local`, `number`, and `range`, the `step` attribute is a number that specifies the granularity that the value must adhere to.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Only values which are a whole number of steps from the step base are valid.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The step base is `min` if specified, `value` otherwise, or `0` if neither is provided (except for `week`, which has a default step base of −259,200,000, representing the start of week `1970-W01`).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The value must be a positive number—integer or float—or the special value `any`, which means no stepping is implied, and any value is allowed (barring other constraints, such as `min` and `max`).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For example, if you have `<input type="number" min="10" step="2">`, then any even integer, `10` or greater, is valid.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If omitted, `<input type="number">`, any integer is valid, but floats (like `4.2`) are not valid, because `step` defaults to `1`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For `4.2` to be valid, `step` would have had to be set to `any`, 0.1, 0.2, or the `min` value would have had to be a number ending in `.2`, such as `<input type="number" min="-5.2">`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for `checkbox` input only, `switch` is a Boolean attribute that indicates whether the checkbox input should be rendered as a switch.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Global attribute valid for all elements, including all the input types, an integer attribute indicating if the element can take input focus (is focusable), if it should participate to sequential keyboard navigation.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] As all input types except for input of type hidden are focusable, this attribute should not be used on form controls, because doing so would require the management of the focus order for all elements within the document with the risk of harming usability and accessibility if done incorrectly.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Global attribute valid for all elements, including all input types, containing a text representing advisory information related to the element it belongs to.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Such information can typically, but not necessarily, be presented to the user as a tooltip.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The title should NOT be used as the primary explanation of the purpose of the form control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Instead, use the `<label>` element with a `for` attribute set to the form control's `id` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A string specifying the type of control to render.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For example, to create a checkbox, a value of `checkbox` is used.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If omitted (or an unknown value is specified), the input type `text` is used, creating a plaintext input field.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Permitted values are listed in Input types above.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When specified in the HTML, this is the initial value, and from then on it can be altered or retrieved at any time using JavaScript to access the respective `HTMLInputElement` object's `value` property.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `value` attribute is always optional, though should be considered mandatory for `checkbox`, `radio`, and `hidden`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Valid for the `image` input button only, the `width` is the width of the image file to display to represent the graphical submit button.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The following non-standard attributes are also available on some browsers.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] As a general rule, you should avoid using them unless it can't be helped.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The Boolean attribute `incremental` is a WebKit and Blink extension (so supported by Safari, Opera, Chrome, etc.) which, if present, tells the user agent to process the input as a live search.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] As the user edits the value of the field, the user agent sends `search` events to the `HTMLInputElement` object representing the search box.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This allows your code to update the search results in real time as the user edits the search.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If `incremental` is not specified, the `search` event is only sent when the user explicitly initiates a search (such as by pressing the Enter or Return key while editing the field).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `search` event is rate-limited so that it is not sent more frequently than an implementation-defined interval.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Similar to the -moz-orient non-standard CSS property impacting the `<progress>` and `<meter>` elements, the `orient` attribute defines the orientation of the range slider.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Values include `horizontal`, meaning the range is rendered horizontally, and `vertical`, where the range is rendered vertically.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See Creating vertical form controls for a modern approach to creating vertical form controls.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `results` attribute—supported only by Safari—is a numeric value that lets you override the maximum number of entries to be displayed in the `<input>` element's natively-provided drop-down menu of previous search queries.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The value must be a non-negative decimal number.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] If not provided, or an invalid value is given, the browser's default maximum number of entries is used.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The Boolean `webkitdirectory` attribute, if present, indicates that only directories should be available to be selected by the user in the file picker interface.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] See `HTMLInputElement.webkitdirectory` for additional details and examples.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Though originally implemented only for WebKit-based browsers, `webkitdirectory` is also usable in Microsoft Edge as well as Firefox 50 and later.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] However, even though it has relatively broad support, it is still not standard and should not be used unless you have no alternative.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The following methods are provided by the `HTMLInputElement` interface which represents `<input>` elements in the DOM.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Also available are those methods specified by the parent interfaces, `HTMLElement`, `Element`, `Node`, and `EventTarget`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Returns `true` if the element's value passes validity checks; otherwise, returns `false` and fires an `invalid` event at the element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Returns `true` if the element's value passes validity checks; otherwise, returns `false`, fires an `invalid` event at the element, and (if the event isn't canceled) reports the problem to the user.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Selects the entire content of the `<input>` element, if the element's content is selectable.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] For elements with no selectable text content (such as a visual color picker or calendar date input), this method does nothing.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Sets a custom message to display if the input element's value isn't valid.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Sets the contents of the specified range of characters in the input element to a given string.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] A `selectMode` parameter is available to allow controlling how the existing content is affected.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Selects the specified range of characters within a textual input element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Does nothing for inputs which aren't presented as text input fields.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Displays the browser picker for the input element that would normally be displayed when the element is selected, but triggered from a button press or other user interaction.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Decrements the value of a numeric input by one, by default, or by the specified number of units.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Increments the value of a numeric input by one or by the specified number of units.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Inputs, being replaced elements, have a few features not applicable to non form elements.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] There are CSS selectors that can specifically target form controls based on their UI features, also known as UI pseudo-classes.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The input element can also be targeted by type with attribute selectors.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] There are some properties that are especially useful as well.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] We can style a checkbox label based on whether the checkbox is checked or not.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] In this example, we are styling the `color` and `font-weight` of the `<label>` that comes immediately after a checked input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] We haven't applied any styles if the `input` is not checked.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] It is possible to target different types of form controls based on their `type` using attribute selectors.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] CSS attribute selectors match elements based on either just the presence of an attribute or the value of a given attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] By default, the appearance of placeholder text is a translucent or light gray.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `::placeholder` pseudo-element is the input's `placeholder` text.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] It can be styled with a limited subset of CSS properties.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] Only the subset of CSS properties that apply to the `::first-line` pseudo-element can be used in a rule using `::placeholder` in its selector.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] The `field-sizing` property enables you to control the sizing behavior of form inputs (i.e., they are given a default preferred size by default.) This property enables you to override the default behavior, allowing form controls to adjust in size to fit their contents.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This property is typically used to create form fields that shrinkwrap their content and grow as more text is entered.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] This works with input types that accept direct text input (for example, `text` and `url`), input type `file`, and `<textarea>` elements.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] In certain cases (typically involving non-textual inputs and specialized interfaces), the `<input>` element is a replaced element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p01] When it is, the position and size of the element's size and positioning within its frame can be adjusted using the CSS `object-position` and `object-fit` properties.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Labels are needed to associate assistive text with an `<input>`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The `<label>` element provides explanatory information about a form field that is *always* appropriate (aside from any layout concerns you have).
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] It's never a bad idea to use a `<label>` to explain what should be entered into an `<input>` or `<textarea>`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The semantic pairing of `<input>` and `<label>` elements is useful for assistive technologies such as screen readers.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] By pairing them using the `<label>`'s `for` attribute, you bond the label to the input in a way that lets screen readers describe inputs to users more precisely.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] It does not suffice to have plain text adjacent to the `<input>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The first example is inaccessible: no relationship exists between the prompt and the `<input>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] In addition to an accessible name, the label provides a larger 'hit' area for mouse and touch screen users to click on or touch.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] By pairing a `<label>` with an `<input>`, clicking on either one will focus the `<input>`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If you use plain text to "label" your input, this won't happen.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Having the prompt part of the activation area for the input is helpful for people with motor control conditions.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] As web developers, it's important that we never assume that people will know all the things that we know.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The `placeholder` attribute lets you specify text that appears within the `<input>` element's content area itself when it is empty.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The placeholder should never be required to understand your forms.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] It is not a label, and should not be used as a substitute, because it isn't.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The placeholder is used to provide a hint as to what an inputted value should look like, not an explanation or prompt.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Not only is the placeholder not accessible to screen readers, but once the user enters any text into the form control, or if the form control already has a value, the placeholder disappears.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Browsers with automatic page translation features may skip over attributes when translating, meaning the `placeholder` may not get translated.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] In addition to using CSS to style inputs based on the `:valid` or `:invalid` UI states based on the current state of each input, as noted in the UI pseudo-classes section above, the browser provides for client-side validation on (attempted) form submission.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] On form submission, if there is a form control that fails constraint validation, supporting browsers will display an error message on the first invalid form control; displaying a default message based on the error type, or a message set by you.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Some input types and other attributes place limits on what values are valid for a given input.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If a form control doesn't have the `required` attribute, no value, or an empty string, is not invalid.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Even if the above attributes are present, with the exception of `required`, an empty string will not lead to an error.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] We can set limits on what values we accept, and supporting browsers will natively validate these form values and alert the user if there is a mistake when the form is submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] In addition to the errors described in the table above, the `validityState` interface contains the `badInput`, `valid`, and `customError` boolean readonly properties.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] For each of these Boolean properties, a value of `true` indicates that the specified reason validation may have failed is true, with the exception of the `valid` property, which is `true` if the element's value obeys all constraints.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If there is an error, supporting browsers will both alert the user and prevent the form from being submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] A word of caution: if a custom error is set to a truthy value (anything other than the empty string or `null`), the form will be prevented from being submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If there is no custom error message, and none of the other properties return true, `valid` will be true, and the form can be submitted.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The last line, setting the custom validity message to the empty string is vital.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If the user makes an error, and the validity is set, it will fail to submit, even if all the values are valid, until the message is `null`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] If you want to present a custom error message when a field fails to validate, you need to use the Constraint Validation API available on `<input>` (and related) elements.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The basic HTML form validation features will cause this to produce a default error message if you try to submit the form with either no valid filled in, or a value that does not match the `pattern`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The allowed inputs for certain `<input>` types depend on the locale.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] In some locales, 1,000.00 is a valid number, while in other locales the valid way to enter this number is 1.000,00.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] When including inputs, it is an accessibility requirement to add labels alongside.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] This is needed so those who use assistive technologies can tell what the input is for.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Also, clicking or touching a label gives focus to the label's associated form control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] This improves the accessibility and usability for sighted users, increases the area a user can click or touch to activate the form control.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] This is especially useful (and even needed) for radio buttons and checkboxes, which are tiny.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] For more information about labels in general see Labels.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The following is an example of how to associate the `<label>` with an `<input>` element in the above style.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] You need to give the `<input>` an `id` attribute.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] The `<label>` then needs a `for` attribute whose value is the same as the input's `id`.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] Interactive elements such as form input should provide an area large enough that it is easy to activate them.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] This helps a variety of people, including people with motor control issues and people using non-precise forms of input such as a stylus or fingers.
[src:web-platform/element-input-p02] A minimum interactive size of 44×44 CSS pixels is recommended.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The **`<table>`** HTML element represents tabular data—that is, information presented in a two-dimensional table comprised of rows and columns of cells containing data.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The following attributes are deprecated and should not be used.
[src:web-platform/element-table] They are documented below for reference when updating existing code and for historical interest only.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Specifies the horizontal alignment of the table within its parent element.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The possible enumerated values are `left`, `center`, and `right`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `margin-inline-start` and `margin-inline-end` CSS properties instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines the background color of the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The value is an HTML color; either a 6-digit hexadecimal RGB code, prefixed by a `#`, or a color keyword.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Other CSS `<color>` values are not supported.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `background-color` CSS property instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines, as a non-negative integer value (in pixels), the size of the frame surrounding the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] If set to `0`, the `frame` attribute is set to void.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `border` CSS property instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines the space between the content of a cell and its border.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This attribute is obsolete: instead of using it, apply the `padding` CSS property to the `<th>` and `<td>` elements.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines the size of the space between two cells.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This attribute is obsolete: instead of using it, set the `border-spacing` CSS property on the `<table>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Note that this has no effect if the `<table>` element's `border-collapse` CSS property is set to `collapse`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines which side of the frame surrounding the table must be displayed.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The possible enumerated values are `void`, `above`, `below`, `hsides`, `vsides`, `lhs`, `rhs`, `box` and `border`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `border-style` and `border-width` CSS properties instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines where rules (borders) are displayed in the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The possible enumerated values are `none` (default value), `groups` (`<thead>`, `<tbody>`, and `<tfoot>` elements), `rows` (horizontal lines), `cols` (vertical lines), and `all` (border around every cell).
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `border` CSS property on the appropriate table-related elements, as well as on the `<table>` itself, instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Defines an alternative text that summarizes the content of the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `<caption>` element instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Use the `width` CSS property instead, as this attribute is deprecated.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The `<table>` box establishes a table formatting context.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Elements inside the `<table>` generate rectangular boxes.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A row group box occupies one or more row boxes.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Column boxes are placed next to each other in source code order.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Depending on the value of the `dir` attribute, the columns are laid in left-to-right or right-to-left direction.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A column box occupies one or more columns of table cells.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A column group box occupies one or more column boxes.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A cell box may span over multiple rows and columns.
[src:web-platform/element-table] User agents trim cells to fit in the available number of rows and columns.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Boxes that make up a table do not have margins.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The background set on an element in one layer will be visible only if the layers above it have transparent background.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A missing cell is rendered as if an anonymous table-cell box occupied that place.
[src:web-platform/element-table] By supplying a `<caption>` element whose value clearly and concisely describes the table's purpose, it helps the people decide if they need to check the rest of the table content or skip over it.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This helps people navigating with the aid of assistive technology such as a screen reader, people experiencing low vision conditions, and people with cognitive concerns.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The `scope` attribute on header cells (`<th>` elements) is redundant in simple contexts, because scope is inferred.
[src:web-platform/element-table] However, some assistive technologies may fail to draw correct inferences, so specifying header scope may improve user experiences.
[src:web-platform/element-table] In complex tables, `scope` can be specified to provide necessary information about the cells related to a header.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Assistive technologies such as screen readers may have difficulty parsing tables that are so complex that header cells can't be associated in a strictly horizontal or vertical way.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This is typically indicated by the presence of the `colspan` and `rowspan` attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Ideally, consider alternate ways to present the table's content, including breaking it apart into a collection of smaller, related tables that don't have to rely on using the `colspan` and `rowspan` attributes.
[src:web-platform/element-table] In addition to helping people who use assistive technology understand the table's content, this may also benefit people with cognitive concerns who may have difficulty understanding the associations the table layout is describing.
[src:web-platform/element-table] If the table cannot be broken apart, use a combination of the `id` and `headers` attributes to programmatically associate each table cell with the header(s) (`<th>` elements) the cell is associated with.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The examples below include tables of progressively increasing complexity.
[src:web-platform/element-table] See also our beginner's Styling tables guide for table styling information including common, useful techniques.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Since the structure of a `<table>` involves the use of several table-related HTML elements along with various associated attributes, the following examples are intended to provide a simplified explanation that covers the basics and common standards.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Additional and more detailed information can be found on the corresponding linked pages.
[src:web-platform/element-table] These table examples demonstrate how to create an accessible table that is structured with HTML and styled with CSS.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Because of how HTML tables are structured, the markup can quickly grow.
[src:web-platform/element-table] For this reason, it is important to clearly define the table's purpose and final appearance to create the appropriate structure.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A logical structure developed with semantic markup is not only easier to style, but enables useful and accessible tables that can be understood and navigated by everyone, including search engines and users of assistive technologies.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The first example is basic, with subsequent examples growing in complexity.
[src:web-platform/element-table] First, we will develop a very basic HTML table structure for the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The first two examples contain no table section groups such as a defined head, body, or foot, and involve no cell spanning or explicitly defined cell relationships.
[src:web-platform/element-table] As we work through the examples, they will be progressively enhanced to include all the table features that a complex data table should possess.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This example includes a *very* basic table with three rows and two columns.
[src:web-platform/element-table] To demonstrate default browser table styles, no CSS has been included in this example.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The table rows are defined with `<tr>` elements, and the columns are defined with table header and data cells within them.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The first row contains the header cells (`<th>` elements) that serve as column headers for the data cells (`<td>` elements).
[src:web-platform/element-table] Each element (`<th>` or `<td>`) per row is in its respective column—that is, the first element of a row is in the first column, and the second element of that row is in the second column.
[src:web-platform/element-table] There is no custom CSS or user stylesheet applied to this table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The styling results purely from the user-agent stylesheet.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This example extends the basic table, extending the content and adding basic CSS styles.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The table comprises four rows (`<tr>` elements) now, with four columns each.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The first row is a row of header cells (The first row contains only `<th>` elements).
[src:web-platform/element-table] Subsequent rows include a header column (`<th>` elements as the first child elements of each row) and three data columns (`<td>` elements).
[src:web-platform/element-table] As table sectioning elements are not used, the browser automatically defines the content group structure, i.e., all rows are wrapped within the body of the table of an implicit `<tbody>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-table] With CSS, we provide the basic styling to create lines around the components of the table to make the data structure clearer.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The CSS adds a solid border around the `<table>` and around each of the table's cells, including those specified with both `<th>` and `<td>` elements, demarcating every header and data cells.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Before moving on to extend the table in more advanced ways, it's advisable to improve accessibility by defining relationships between the header and data cells (`<th>` and `<td>` elements).
[src:web-platform/element-table] This is accomplished by introducing the `scope` attribute on the `<th>` elements and setting the values to the corresponding `col` (column) or `row` value.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The CSS and visual result are unchanged—the adaptation provides valuable contextual information for assistive technologies such as screen readers to help identify which cells the headers relate to.
[src:web-platform/element-table] In addition to improving accessibility by specifying cell relations, the semantics of the table can be improved by introducing table section groups.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Since the first row (`<tr>` element) contains only column header cells and provides the header for the rest of the table's contents, it can be enclosed in the `<thead>` element to explicitly specify that row as the head section of the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Moreover, what is automatically accomplished by the browser can also be defined explicitly—the body section of the table, which contains the main data of the table, is specified by enclosing the corresponding rows in the `<tbody>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The explicit use of the `<tbody>` element helps the browser to create the intended table structure, avoiding unwanted results.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Once again, the CSS and visual result are unchanged—specifying such table section groups provides valuable contextual information for assistive technologies, including screen readers and search engines, as well as for styling in the CSS, which will be shown in a later example.
[src:web-platform/element-table] In this example, we extend the table even more by adding a column and introducing a multi-row head section.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Building on the table created so far, a new column for a "Membership End Date" is added in each body row with the `<td>` element.
[src:web-platform/element-table] An additional row (`<tr>` element) is also added within the head section (`<thead>` element) to introduce a "Membership Dates" header as a heading for the "Joined" and "Canceled" columns.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The creation of the second header row involves adding `colspan` and `rowspan` attributes to the `<th>` elements to allocate the header cells to the correct columns and rows.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The head section now has two rows, one with the headers (`<th>` elements) "Name", "ID", "Membership Dates", and "Balance", and a "Membership Dates" header with two subheaders that are in a second row: "Joined" and "Canceled".
[src:web-platform/element-table] It's a common and advisable practice to provide a summary for the table's content, allowing users to quickly determine the table's relevance.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Furthermore, the "Balance" column is summarized by displaying the sum of the balances of the individual members.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A table summary is added by using a table caption (`<caption>` element) as the first child element of the `<table>`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The caption provides the accessible name or accessible description for the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Lastly, a table foot section (`<tfoot>` element) is added below the body, with a row that summarizes the "Balance" column by displaying a sum.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The elements and attributes introduced earlier are applied.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Let's apply a basic style to the table to adjust the typeface and add a `background-color` to the head and foot rows.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The HTML is unchanged this time, so let's dive right into the CSS.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This is a way to quickly apply a background color to all the cells in specific sections simultaneously.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Now we'll go all-out, with styles on rows in the header and body areas both, including alternating row colors, cells with different colors depending on position within a row, and so forth.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Let's take a look at the result first this time.
[src:web-platform/element-table] See what proper preparation of the HTML structure can do?
[src:web-platform/element-table] The CSS is much more involved this time.
[src:web-platform/element-table] It's not complicated, but there's a lot going on.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Here the `border-collapse` and `border-spacing` properties are added to eliminate spacing between cells and collapse borders that touch one another to be a single border instead of winding up with double borders.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Next, the `padding` property is used to give all the table cells space around their content.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The next CSS rule sets the `background-color` of all `<tr>` elements in the table's head (as specified using `<thead>`).
[src:web-platform/element-table] Then the bottom border of the head is set to be a two-pixel wide line.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Notice, however, that we're using the `:nth-of-type` selector to apply the `border-bottom` property to the *second* row in the head.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Because the head is made of two rows that are spanned by some of the cells.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Let's style the two header cells "Joined" and "Canceled" with green and red hues to represent the "good" of a new member and the "bummer" of a canceled membership.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Since the first column should stand out as well, some custom styling is added here too.
[src:web-platform/element-table] It's common to help improve the readability of table data by alternating row colors—this is sometimes referred to as "zebra striping".
[src:web-platform/element-table] Since it's standard practice to right-justify currency values in tables, let's do that here.
[src:web-platform/element-table] A common issue with tables on the web is that they don't natively work very well on small screens when the amount of content is large, and the way to make them scrollable isn't obvious, especially when the markup may come from a CMS and cannot be modified to have a wrapper.
[src:web-platform/element-table] This example provides one way to display tables in small spaces.
[src:web-platform/element-table] We've hidden the HTML content as it is very large, and there is nothing remarkable about it.
[src:web-platform/element-table] The CSS is more useful to inspect in this example.
[src:web-platform/element-table] When looking at these styles you'll notice that table's `display` property has been set to `block`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] While this allows scrolling, the table loses some of its integrity, and table cells try to become as small as possible.
[src:web-platform/element-table] To mitigate this issue we've set `white-space` to `nowrap` on the `<tbody>`.
[src:web-platform/element-table] However, we don't do this for the `<thead>` to avoid long titles forcing columns to be wider than they need to be to display the data.
[src:web-platform/element-table] To keep the table headers on the page while scrolling down we've set `position` to sticky on the `<th>` elements.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Note that we have **not** set `border-collapse` to `collapse`, as if we do the header cannot be separated correctly from the rest of the table.
[src:web-platform/element-table] Given that the `<table>` has a fixed size, the `overflow` set to `auto` is the important part here, as it makes the table scrollable.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:web-platform/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) connects web pages to scripts or programming languages by representing the structure of a document—such as the HTML representing a web page—in memory.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Usually it refers to JavaScript, even though modeling HTML, SVG, or XML documents as objects are not part of the core JavaScript language.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:web-platform/introduction] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree.
[src:web-platform/introduction] With them, you can change the document's structure, style, or content.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Nodes can also have event handlers attached to them.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web documents.
[src:web-platform/introduction] It represents the page so that programs can change the document structure, style, and content.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM represents the document as nodes and objects; that way, programming languages can interact with the page.
[src:web-platform/introduction] A web page is a document that can be either displayed in the browser window or as the HTML source.
[src:web-platform/introduction] In both cases, it is the same document but the Document Object Model (DOM) representation allows it to be manipulated.
[src:web-platform/introduction] As an object-oriented representation of the web page, it can be modified with a scripting language such as JavaScript.
[src:web-platform/introduction] All of the properties, methods, and events available for manipulating and creating web pages are organized into objects.
[src:web-platform/introduction] For example, the `document` object that represents the document itself, any `table` objects that implement the `HTMLTableElement` DOM interface for accessing HTML tables, and so forth, are all objects.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM is built using multiple APIs that work together.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The core DOM defines the entities describing any document and the objects within it.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This is expanded upon as needed by other APIs that add new features and capabilities to the DOM.
[src:web-platform/introduction] For example, the HTML DOM API adds support for representing HTML documents to the core DOM, and the SVG API adds support for representing SVG documents.
[src:web-platform/introduction] A **DOM tree** is a tree structure whose nodes represent an HTML or XML document's contents.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Each HTML or XML document has a DOM tree representation.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Although the above tree is similar to the above document's DOM tree, they're not identical, as the actual DOM tree preserves whitespace.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When a web browser parses an HTML document, it builds a DOM tree and then uses it to display the document.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The previous short example, like nearly all examples, is JavaScript.
[src:web-platform/introduction] That is to say, it is *written* in JavaScript, but *uses* the DOM to access the document and its elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM is not a programming language, but without it, the JavaScript language wouldn't have any model or notion of web pages, HTML documents, SVG documents, and their component parts.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The document as a whole, the head, tables within the document, table headers, text within the table cells, and all other elements in a document are parts of the document object model for that document.
[src:web-platform/introduction] They can all be accessed and manipulated using the DOM and a scripting language like JavaScript.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM is not part of the JavaScript language, but is instead a Web API used to build websites.
[src:web-platform/introduction] JavaScript can also be used in other contexts.
[src:web-platform/introduction] For example, Node.js runs JavaScript programs on a computer, but provides a different set of APIs, and the DOM API is not a core part of the Node.js runtime.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The DOM was designed to be independent of any particular programming language, making the structural representation of the document available from a single, consistent API.
[src:web-platform/introduction] For more information on what technologies are involved in writing JavaScript on the web, see JavaScript technologies overview.
[src:web-platform/introduction] You don't have to do anything special to begin using the DOM.
[src:web-platform/introduction] You use the API directly in JavaScript from within what is called a *script*, a program run by a browser.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When you create a script, whether inline in a `<script>` element or included in the web page, you can immediately begin using the API for the `document` or `window` objects to manipulate the document itself, or any of the various elements in the web page (the descendant elements of the document).
[src:web-platform/introduction] As it is generally not recommended to mix the structure of the page (written in HTML) and manipulation of the DOM (written in JavaScript), the JavaScript parts will be grouped together here, and separated from the HTML.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This guide is about the objects and the actual *things* you can use to manipulate the DOM hierarchy.
[src:web-platform/introduction] There are many points where understanding how these work can be confusing.
[src:web-platform/introduction] For example, the object representing the HTML `form` element gets its `name` property from the `HTMLFormElement` interface but its `className` property from the `HTMLElement` interface.
[src:web-platform/introduction] In both cases, the property you want is in that form object.
[src:web-platform/introduction] But the relationship between objects and the interfaces that they implement in the DOM can be confusing, and so this section attempts to say a little something about the actual interfaces in the DOM specification and how they are made available.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Many objects implement several different interfaces.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The table object, for example, implements a specialized `HTMLTableElement` interface, which includes such methods as `createCaption` and `insertRow`.
[src:web-platform/introduction] But since it's also an HTML element, `table` implements the `Element` interface described in the DOM `Element` Reference chapter.
[src:web-platform/introduction] And finally, since an HTML element is also, as far as the DOM is concerned, a node in the tree of nodes that make up the object model for an HTML or XML page, the table object also implements the more basic `Node` interface, from which `Element` derives.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When you get a reference to a `table` object, as in the following example, you routinely use all three of these interfaces interchangeably on the object, perhaps without knowing it.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This page tries to describe the various objects and types in simple terms.
[src:web-platform/introduction] But there are a number of different data types being passed around the API that you should be aware of.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The following table briefly describes these data types.
[src:web-platform/introduction] There are also some common terminology considerations to keep in mind.
[src:web-platform/introduction] It's common to refer to any `Attr` node as an `attribute`, for example, and to refer to an array of DOM nodes as a `nodeList`.
[src:web-platform/introduction] You'll find these terms and others to be introduced and used throughout the documentation.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The `document` and `window` objects are the objects whose interfaces you generally use most often in DOM programming.
[src:web-platform/introduction] In simple terms, the `window` object represents something like the browser, and the `document` object is the root of the document itself.
[src:web-platform/introduction] `Element` inherits from the generic `Node` interface, and together these two interfaces provide many of the methods and properties you use on individual elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] These elements may also have specific interfaces for dealing with the kind of data those elements hold, as in the `table` object example in the previous section.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The Document Object Model has been highly simplified.
[src:web-platform/introduction] To achieve this, the following interfaces in the different DOM level 3 or earlier specifications have been removed.
[src:web-platform/introduction] They are no longer available to web developers.
[src:web-platform/introduction] A document containing HTML is described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the HTML specification to include various HTML-specific features.
[src:web-platform/introduction] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `HTMLElement` and various subclasses, each representing one of (or a family of closely related) elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The HTML DOM API provides access to various browser features such as tabs and windows, CSS styles and stylesheets, browser history, etc.
[src:web-platform/introduction] These interfaces are discussed further in the HTML DOM API documentation.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Similarly, a document containing SVG is also described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the SVG specification to include various SVG-specific features.
[src:web-platform/introduction] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `SVGElement` and various subclasses, each representing an element or a family of closely related elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] These interfaces are discussed further in the SVG API documentation.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<textarea>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When the user clicks the first button we set some text in the `<textarea>`.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When the user clicks the second button we clear the text.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<div>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When the user clicks the first button we create a new element and add it as a child of the `<div>`.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When the user clicks the second button we remove the child element.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Suppose the author wants to change the header of the document in What is a DOM tree? and write two paragraphs instead of one.
[src:web-platform/introduction] You can create the tree in What is a DOM tree? entirely in JavaScript too.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This example demonstrates how events fire and are handled in the DOM in a very simple way.
[src:web-platform/introduction] When the BODY of this HTML document loads, an event listener is registered with the top row of the TABLE.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The event listener handles the event by executing the function stopEvent, which changes the value in the bottom cell of the table.
[src:web-platform/introduction] However, stopEvent also calls an event object method, `event.stopPropagation`, which keeps the event from bubbling any further up into the DOM.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Note that the table itself has an `onclick` event handler that ought to display a message when the table is clicked.
[src:web-platform/introduction] But the stopEvent method has stopped propagation, and so after the data in the table is updated, the event phase is effectively ended, and an alert box is displayed to confirm this.
[src:web-platform/introduction] This example uses DOM methods to display all the properties of the `click` event object and their values in a table.
[src:web-platform/introduction] It also shows a useful technique of using a `for...in` loop to iterate over the properties of an object to get their values.
[src:web-platform/introduction] The properties of event objects differs greatly between browsers, the WHATWG DOM Standard lists the standard properties, however many browsers have extended these greatly.
[src:web-platform/introduction] Put the following code into a blank text file and load it into a variety of browsers, you'll be surprised at the different number and names of properties.
[src:web-platform/introduction] You might also like to add some elements in the page and call this function from different event handlers.
